'''Openbox''' is a highly configurable, next generation window manager with extensive standards support. 

{{Note| This guide is not a replacement to the [http://www.gentoo.org/doc/en/openbox.xml official Gentoo Openbox Guide] at the moment. Its only purpose is to illustrate the changes between version 3.4 and 3.5 .}}

== Installation ==
Install {{Package|x11-wm/openbox}}:
{{USEflag
|package=x11-wm/openbox
|branding
|debug
|imlib
|nls
|session+yes+yes
|startup-notification+yes
|static-libs
}}

{{Emerge|openbox}}

== Configuration ==
There are four files to consider when configuring openbox:
* {{Path|autostart}}
* {{Path|environment}}
* {{Path|menu.xml}}
* {{Path|rc.xml}}

Openbox installs these files to {{Path|/etc/xdg/openbox/}}. If you want to override them, create your own in {{Path|~/.config/openbox/}}.

=== Autostart ===
The {{Path|autostart}} file is the ideal way to execute specific commands and programs when Openbox starts. It makes no difference if you start Openbox using '''startx''' or any display manager. Here is an example:
{{File|~/.config/openbox/autostart||<pre>
wallpaper="planet.jpeg"
DESKTOP_ENV="OPENBOX"
conky --daemonize
sleep 1 && nm-applet --sm-disable &
fbpanel &
feh --bg-scale ~/Artwork/${wallpaper}&
batti &
numlockx &
</pre>}}

=== Environment ===
This is the ideal place to export global variables and configure your openbox environment as appropriate:
{{File|~/.config/openbox/environment||<pre>
eval $(gpg-agent --daemon)
eval $(gnome-keyring-daemon)
if which dbus-launch >/dev/null && test -z "$DBUS_SESSION_BUS_ADDRESS"; then
       eval `dbus-launch --sh-syntax --exit-with-session`
fi
LANG="el_GR.UTF8"
</pre>}}

